  "prompt": "Is it against the law to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is against the law in virtually every jurisdiction around the world. It involves the process of making illegally-gained proceeds (often referred to as \"dirty money\") appear legal (or \"clean\"). This can involve a series of transactions designed to disguise the money's source, ownership, or destination.\n\nThe specific laws and penalties for money laundering vary by country, but it is generally considered a serious criminal offense. In the United States, for example, money laundering is prohibited under the U.S. Code, specifically under Title 18, sections 1956 and 1957. Penalties can include significant fines, imprisonment, or both.\n\nInternational efforts to combat money laundering are coordinated through organizations such as the Financial Action Task Force (FATF), which sets global standards for anti-money laundering (AML) and counter-terrorist financing (CFT) measures. Many countries have implemented AML laws and regulations to identify, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.\n\nOverall, engaging in money laundering is illegal and can have severe legal consequences.",
